body:
When navigating a select box via Home/End/PageUp/PageDown and all options in the traversal direction are disabled, the while loop would halt at the boundary index without verifying that index is itself non-disabled — leaving `this.selected` pointing to a disabled option.

## Changes

- **`onEnd` / `onHome`**: Use a local `target` variable instead of mutating `this.selected` during the loop; add a post-loop guard that returns early if `options[target]` is still disabled (all options disabled edge case).
- **`onPageDown` / `onPageUp`**: Same fix applied to the timeout callbacks that shift focus off disabled items after page scroll.

All four methods now follow the same pattern as `onDownArrow` / `onUpArrow`, which already handled this correctly:

```typescript
// Before — loop exits at boundary without verifying the boundary option itself
this.selected = this.options.length - 1;
while (this.selected > 0 && this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected--;
}
// this.selected may still point to a disabled option

// After — preserve current selection when no enabled option found
let target = this.options.length - 1;
while (target > 0 && this.options[target].isDisabled) {
    target--;
}
if (this.options[target].isDisabled) {
    return;
}
this.selected = target;
```

