`onHome`, `onEnd`, `onPageUp`, and `onPageDown` would leave `this.selected` pointing to a disabled option when all options in the target direction were disabled — the while loop would exhaust without finding a valid candidate.

## Changes

- **`onHome` / `onEnd` / `onPageUp` / `onPageDown`**: Switch from mutating `this.selected` directly during the search to using a local `newSelected` variable. After the loop, if the candidate is still disabled, return early without updating `this.selected`.

```ts
// Before — this.selected could end up on a disabled option
this.selected = 0;
while (this.selected < this.options.length - 1 && this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected++;
}
// this.selected may still be disabled if all options are disabled

// After — early return if no non-disabled option found
let newSelected = 0;
while (newSelected < this.options.length - 1 && this.options[newSelected].isDisabled) {
    newSelected++;
}
if (this.options[newSelected].isDisabled) {
    return;
}
this.selected = newSelected;
```

Consistent with the existing pattern in `onDownArrow` / `onUpArrow`, which already use a local variable and bail out before committing the change.

