When navigating a select box with all-disabled options in the scan range, `this.selected` could be left pointing at a disabled option after Page Up/Down, Home, or End key handling.

## Changes

- **`onPageDown` / `onPageUp`**: Use a local `newSelected` variable instead of mutating `this.selected` during the skip loop. After the loop, if the candidate is still disabled, restore visual focus to the unchanged `this.selected` and return early.
- **`onHome` / `onEnd`**: Same pattern — scan from boundary using a temp variable; only commit to `this.selected` when a valid non-disabled option is confirmed.

This matches the existing pattern in `onUpArrow`, which already used a temp `prev` variable and returned early when no valid option was found.

```ts
// Before: mutated this.selected directly, could end at a disabled option
this.selected = this.selectList.getFocus()[0];
while (this.selected > 0 && this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected--;
}
this.selectList.setFocus([this.selected]); // may set focus on a disabled item

// After: use temp variable, guard before committing
let newSelected = this.selectList.getFocus()[0];
while (newSelected > 0 && this.options[newSelected].isDisabled) {
    newSelected--;
}
if (this.options[newSelected].isDisabled) {
    this.selectList.setFocus([this.selected]); // restore focus, no-op
    return;
}
this.selected = newSelected;
this.selectList.setFocus([this.selected]);
```

