💡 You can make Copilot smarter by setting up custom instructions, customizing its development environment and configuring Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers. Learn more [Copilot coding agent tips](https://gh.io/copilot-coding-agent-tips) in the docs.

`onPageUp`, `onPageDown`, `onHome`, and `onEnd` in `selectBoxCustom.ts` each had a while loop to skip disabled options, but if *all* remaining options were disabled the loop would exit with `this.selected` still pointing to a disabled item — then call `setFocus`/`select` on it anyway.

## Changes

- **`onPageUp` / `onPageDown` / `onHome` / `onEnd`**: Save `previousSelected` before the skip loop; after the loop, check `this.options[this.selected].isDisabled` and restore `this.selected = previousSelected` + return early if no enabled option was found.

```typescript
// Before
while (this.selected < this.options.length - 1 && this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected++;
}
this.selectList.setFocus([this.selected]); // could be a disabled item

// After
const previousSelected = this.selected;
while (this.selected < this.options.length - 1 && this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected++;
}
if (this.options[this.selected].isDisabled) {
    this.selected = previousSelected;
    return;
}
this.selectList.setFocus([this.selected]);
```

This aligns with the existing pattern in `onDownArrow`/`onUpArrow`, which already guard against going out of bounds before updating `this.selected`.

